    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-05T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-05T14:00:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 EW/9–544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-05T22:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 5, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 5—3:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3325. ReEmbs 3321, September 5, 7 p.m. After Molotov had informed the British
                    Ambassador and myself of the Soviet declaration of war on Bulgaria, I inquired
                    whether Russian troops would enter Bulgaria. Molotov replied that this was a
                    military question which had not been discussed and which would depend on
                    developments. I asked whether the Soviet Government would prefer the Bulgars to
                    cave in. He replied that it was difficult to say and that it was quite possible
                    that the Bulgarians had foreseen this development as the Soviets had publicly
                    made plain their dissatisfaction with Bulgaria’s continued aid to Germany and
                    unwillingness to join the democratic camp.</p>
                <p>I would not be surprised if the Soviet Government’s desire to be party to
                    Bulgarian armistice and control of its execution did not play an important part
                    in the Soviet Government’s declaration of war.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated for the secret information of the Ambassadors to
                    AmEmbassy London as 161, AmEmbassy Ankara, AmEmBalk Cairo for MacVeagh.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
